-- BHP, Nufarm, Macarthur, Virgin Blue, Woodside: Australian Equity Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-09-26T22:16:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-26/bhp-nufarm-macarthur-virgin-blue-woodside-australian-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of
companies whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This
preview includes news announced after markets closed on Sept. 24.
All prices are from that day’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December rose
1.2 percent to 4,677 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index  gained 2.7 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200
Index  lost 0.7 percent to 4,601.90.  Mining shares: Copper futures for December delivery rose
0.8 percent to settle at $3.618 a pound at 1:22 p.m. in New York.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, declined 0.5 percent to A$39.04 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts gained 2.6 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
fell 0.6 percent to A$75.60 in Sydney.  Oil companies: Crude for November delivery rose 1.7 percent
to $76.49 a barrel in New York, the highest settlement since
Sept. 13.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, added 0.1 percent to A$44.48.
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) gained 0.9 percent to A$12.83.  Macarthur Coal Ltd.  (MCC AU): The world’s largest producer
of pulverized coal said it would pay about 1 percent to 2
percent more tax under Australia’s revised proposed levy on
mining profits. Macarthur shares climbed 1.4 percent to A$11.86.  Murchison Metals Ltd.  (MMX AU): Mitsubishi Corp. may pull
out from a A$4 billion ($3.8 billion) Oakajee Port & Rail Pty
iron ore port venture with Australia’s Murchison Metals because
of doubts on its economic viability, the Australian reported,
without citing anyone. Murchison shares fell 2.2 percent to
A$1.81.  Nufarm Ltd.  (NUF AU): Nufarm may be close to agreement with
its banks to secure waivers covering A$1.6 billion of debt
facilities before the company reports full-year earnings
tomorrow, the Australian Financial Review said, citing sources
close to the negotiations that it didn’t identify. The stock
slipped 1.7 percent to A$4.05.       Virgin Blue Holdings Ltd.  (VBA AU)): A computer glitch
affecting check-in counters at Virgin Blue left thousands of
passengers in Australia stranded, the Australian newspaper
reported on its website on Sept. 26, citing Virgin Blue
spokesman  Colin Lippiatt . The stock slumped 3.4 percent to 43
Australian cents.  Telstra Corp.  (TLS AU): Australia’s largest telephone
company will double its redundancy budget to more than A$100
million this fiscal year as it aims to cut jobs to counter
falling fixed-line revenue, the Australian Financial Review
reported. Telstra shares retreated 0.4 percent to A$2.67.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Shani Raja  in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 